Now, Yugy, to address some of your points specifically:<br>
<br>
I do agree with the concept that every class should not be balanced equally for the same style of gameplay, even if it is considered by many players to be the best.  In the case of wizards, this means that their best fit is not in a single pull xp group, unless they are the only snarer.  However, I do object to suggesting that a wizard should spend his time mostly in AE groups.  From a purely selfish perspective, IE xp gained and fun had per hour for <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  me</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, then sure AE groups or soloing is the way to go.  But AE groups, no matter how great they are, are still just a small subset of the grouping possibilities available in the game.  I think that just as every class shouldn't be balanced for the same kind of gameplay, nor should any class be overbalanced for another kind.<br>
<br>
One issue that was only briefly touched upon in this thread is the power of an Enchanter.  A good enchanter can turn most of the common pull situations into a series of single target encounters.  Single target nukes may save the enchanter the need to recast mez once or maybe even a few times every once in awhile, otherwise at high levels, selective nuking in experience groups isn't really as useful as it should be.  I've made up some spreadsheets myself that try to evaluate the amount of damage a smart nuker can save a group, but they are very complicated(4+ variables minimum).  But I have been very disappointed so far at my results, which show fairly trivial amounts of savings whenever there is an Enchanter present.<br>
<br>
From even a wizard who does not have trouble getting into groups, their long term damage is a concern.  My perspective is this:  Since we can show that there is indeed a descrepency here that could be adjusted without too much difficulty, what good reasons are there <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to make changes?  Saying things are fine the way they are, and even saying why they are fine the way they are isn't a bad thing, I often do it myself when trying to encourage others to have fun playing their characters rather than griping about things.  However, saying things are fine the way they are does not necessarily mean that changes would not be a good thing.  At this point, since Armok has shown, at least from a certian perspective, that helpful changes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  could</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and even <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be made, it is far more important now to focus on why such changes should not be made.<br>
<br>
